        <h2>What Is This?</h2>
        <p><strong>Byzantine Doors</strong> is a free resource for anyone curious about Eastern Christianity — the ancient tradition of icons and incense, of chanted liturgies and golden domes, of monks in the desert and theologians who dared to say that humans can become God by grace.</p>

        <p>Whether you're a lifelong Byzantine Christian looking for ways to explain your tradition to friends, a Western Christian discovering that your own heritage has an Eastern half, or someone who has never heard the word "Theotokos" and just wants to understand what's behind those golden doors — this site is for you.</p>

        <h2>Our Mission</h2>
        <p>Eastern Christianity is one of the richest spiritual and intellectual traditions in human history. It is also one of the least understood in the English-speaking world. Byzantine Doors exists to bridge that gap — not by simplifying or diluting the tradition, but by presenting it clearly, honestly, and beautifully.</p>

        <p>We believe that good theology deserves good writing. We believe that ancient traditions can speak to modern people without being modernized. We believe that the best way to introduce someone to Eastern Christianity is not with a textbook but with an open door.</p>

        <h2>What We Are Not</h2>
        <p>Byzantine Doors is <strong>not affiliated with any single parish, eparchy, or jurisdiction</strong>. We are not an official organ of any church. We are not here to proselytize, recruit, or argue.</p>

        <p>We are not anti-Western. Eastern and Western Christianity are two expressions of the same apostolic faith — two lungs of the same Body, as Pope St. John Paul II famously said. We present the Eastern perspective because it is underrepresented, not because it is superior.</p>

        <p>We are not anti-Orthodox. Byzantine Doors draws from the shared heritage of all Eastern Christians — Eastern Catholic, Orthodox, and Oriental. The painful divisions between these communities are real, but the tradition they share is deeper than what divides them.</p>

        <h2>Our Sources</h2>
        <p>Content on Byzantine Doors is aligned with standard Eastern Christian theology, drawing primarily from:</p>

        <ul class="about-sources">
          <li><strong>Christ Our Pascha</strong> — the official catechism of the Ukrainian Greek Catholic Church, a comprehensive statement of Eastern Catholic faith</li>
          <li><strong>The Church Fathers</strong> — Athanasius, Basil, Gregory of Nyssa, Gregory of Nazianzus, John Chrysostom, Maximus the Confessor, John of Damascus, and others</li>
          <li><strong>Official liturgical texts</strong> — the Divine Liturgy of St. John Chrysostom, the Horologion, the Festal Menaion</li>
          <li><strong>Academic scholarship</strong> — peer-reviewed historical and theological research</li>
        </ul>

        <p>Where theological opinions differ among Eastern Christians, we note the range of views rather than picking sides. Where the Eastern and Western traditions diverge, we present the Eastern perspective irenically — honestly, but without polemic.</p>

        <h2>Where to Start</h2>
        <p>If you're new here, we recommend <strong><a href="/journey/">The Journey</a></strong> — a sixteen-step guided path through Eastern Christianity, from your first encounter with the Divine Liturgy to the deepest questions of theology and practice. Each step is designed to be read in 5-8 minutes, and you can follow them in order or jump to whatever draws you.</p>

        <p>You can also explore the <a href="/library/">Library</a> for standalone deep dives on specific topics, or check the <a href="/tools/">Tools & Guides</a> for practical resources like "Your First Visit to a Byzantine Parish" and the Byzantine Fasting Guide.</p>

        <h2>An Open Invitation</h2>
        <p>The doors of a Byzantine church are heavy. They are often made of dark wood, carved with crosses and saints, and they can look imposing from the outside. But they open. They have always opened. Everyone who pushes through them is welcome.</p>

        <p>That is what this site is: a door. Not the destination — just the entrance. What you find on the other side is up to you.</p>

        <div class="cta-box">
